The Path to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Mass destruction weapons and disarmament represent one of the most difficult challenges the world is currently facing. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote the global common good and find solutions to problems that know no borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a common good of the highest importance.
My interest in this topic is partly based on personal experiences.
My home country, South Korea, suffered under the devastation of conventional warfare and was exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other mass destruction weapons.
Doch gibt es derartige Bedrohungsszenarien selbstverständlich nicht nur in Asien.
Obwohl der Einsatz von Atomwaffen seit langem als Tabu gilt, bleibt die Abrüstung lediglich eine Bestrebung.
Ist nun ein Tabu, das sich bloß auf den Einsatz solcher Waffen bezieht, überhaupt ausreichend?
Wenn es um Kernwaffen geht, treffen Einzelstaaten die wichtigsten Entscheidungen.
Doch spielt die UNO eine entscheidende Rolle dabei.
We offer a central forum in which states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and inform in order to achieve our agreed objectives, and we advocate for them.
Most states have decided to forgo nuclear weapons and have consolidated their commitments under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
Yet some states view such weapons as a status symbol, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against an attack with nuclear weapons, which mainly explains the estimated 26,000 weapons that still exist.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and creating new risks that nuclear weapons will be used.
The world is still concerned about nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is widespread support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
There are also concerns that we are facing a "nuclear renaissance," as nuclear energy is seen as a clean energy alternative during times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that must be protected from proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are immense.
Yet the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let's think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm Institute for International Peace Research), military spending rose last year to over $1.3 trillion.
A decade ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating the total cost of nuclear weapons alone in the United States at over $5.8 trillion, including future cleanup costs.
This is, by any definition, a huge investment that could have been used for many other productive purposes.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the inherent dangers they pose have led to a global idea spark, giving new life to the concept of nuclear disarmament.
We have witnessed the UN Disarmament Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan have founded the International Commission on Nuclear Non-proliferation and Disarmament.
Civil society groups and states possessing nuclear weapons have also proposed suggestions, such as the Hoover Plan, introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
Firstly: I call on all members of the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty, especially the nuclear-armed states, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and to initiate negotiations on effective measures leading to nuclear disarmament.
You could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or you could negotiate a nuclear weapons convention supported by a strong control system, as has long been proposed by the UN.
I have sent a draft of such a convention to all UN members, which provides a good starting point.
The nuclear powers should actively engage with this issue together with other states at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the only multilateral negotiation forum for disarmament in the world.
The world would welcome the resumption of bilateral negotiations between the United States and Russia with the aim of substantially and verifiably disarming their arsenals.
The governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The UK's proposal to hold a conference of nuclear powers on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should begin to discuss security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly communicate to the states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not be victims of a nuclear weapon use or threat thereof.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should halt their nuclear weapons programs and undertake their own disarmament obligations.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoria on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials should only be allowed to a limited extent.
We need new efforts to bring the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty into force, as well as encouragement to ensure that the Disarmament Conference immediately and without preconditions starts negotiations on a treaty on fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly endorse efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
Furthermore, I urgently call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to conclude their security agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily implement the stricter security clauses of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: The nuclear powers often circulate descriptions of what they do to achieve these goals.
Yet these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to ask the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no significant estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various complementary measures are required.
These include the elimination of other types of mass destruction weapons, new efforts against terrorism using mass destruction weapons, a limitation of the production and trade of conventional weapons and new weapon bans, among others for rockets and space weapons.
If there are real, verified progress in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the nuclear threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the deadliest weapons in the world and their components, we make it harder to carry out terrorist attacks using mass destruction weapons.
These proposals offer a new beginning, not only for disarmament, but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
